RED ARROW DELIVERY SERVICE, AS THE TRANSPORTATION CARRIER ACCEPTED THIS SHIPMENT IN GOOD FAITH AND CONDITION WITH PROPER PAPER WORK AND REQUIRED PLACARDS.  IN ROUTE ONE DRUM STARTED SPEWING LIQUID CORROSIVE INSIDE THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER PULLED INTO THE FIRST AVAILABLE LOCATION TO INVESTIGATE THE PROBLEM.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT (501-633-2414) WAS CALLED IN AND THE AREA WAS CORDONED OFF.  CONSIGNEE (VELSICOL CHEMICAL CO., MEMPHIS, TN. OFFICE) WAS NOTIFIED.  THEY CALLED IN THEIR OWN CLEAN-UP (FERGUSON HARBOR CO.) AS A EMERGENCY RESPONSE AGENT.  THEY REMOVED COMPELTE SHIPMENT (TOTAL OF 4 DRUMS) FROM OUR TRAILER AND CARRIED THEM TO VELISCOL CHEMICAL CO. IN MEMPHIS, TN.  OUR DRIVER WAS ALLOWED TO COMPLETE HIS TRIP TO OUR TERMINAL IN MEMPHIS TN.  A SUPERVISOR FOR OUR COMPANY CONTACTED VELISCOL CHEMICAL TO FIND OUT STATUS OF INCIDENT OCCURRENCE AND ASKED TO LOOK AT DAMAGED DRUM TO DETEMINE CAUSE OF SPILLAGE.  VELISCOL CHEMICAL CO REFUSED OUR REQUEST OF ANY VISUAL CONTACT OF SHIPMENT.  WHEN WE CONTACTED FERGUSON HARBOR (CLEAN UP CO.) WE WERE TOLD THAT VELISCOL CHEMICAL CO WAS THEIR CLIENT AND WERE RESPONSIBLE FOR ALL COSTS, (CURRENT AND ANY REOCCURRENCE). THEY STATED THAT POSSIBLE OVERFILLING THE DRUM HAD CAUSED THE BUNG HOLE PLUG TO LOOSEN AND ALLOWED MOISTURE TO MIX WITH CHEMICALS AND CAUSE THE REACTION.  THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF SPILLAGE ON THE GROUND, NO DAMAGE TO OUR TRAILER OR FREIGHT AND NO REPORTED INJURIES AS A RESULT OF THIS CHEMICAL INCIDENT.

column168: THE INCIDENT THAT OCCURRED AT YOUR MARLBORO FACILITY WAS CAUSED BY OUR DRIVER FOLLOWING PROCEDURE WHICH WE NOW MUST CHANGE AFTER THIS PARTICULAR INCIDENT HAS ACCURRED.  OIL TANK LINES, INC TRAINS OUR DRIVERS TO REMOVE THE HOSES, HOOK UP TO TRAILER DISCHARGE PIPE, OPEN VALVES AND BEFORE STARTING THE PUMP, DO A WALK AROUND TO CHECK FOR LEAKS.  AFTER THE ABOVE STEPS TOOK PLACE, THE DRIVER FOUND THAT THE RIGHT HAND CAP EARS (OPW) WERE LOOSE, THEREFORE 1-4 GALLONS OF PRODUCT ESCAPED.  AT OIL TANK LINES, INC WE USE PLASTIC TIES TO HOLD THESE EARS TOGETHER.  HOWEVER, BECAUSE WE UNLOADED ON THE OPPOSITE SIDE OF THE TRUCK, WE CUT THE LEFT HAND PLASTIC TIE HOOKED UP OUR HOSE, OPENED THE VALVES AND THE RIGHT EARS SHOULD HAVE BEEN WIRED TOGETHER, BECAUSE THEY WEREN'T, THE PROBLEM OCCURRRED.

THE ASHLAND DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE CUSTOMER AT 0950.  1000 GAL. OF PRODUCT WAS BEING DELIVERED.  FOR APPROVAL TO UNLOAD, THE CUSTOMER TOOK A SAMPLE OF THE PRODUCT FOR TESTING.  UPON RECEIVING PERMISSION TO BEGIN UNLOADING, THE DRIVER COMMENCED AT 1150.  THE DRIVER MUST CONNECT HIS HOSE TO THE CUSTOMER'S FITTING LOCATED THREE FEET ABOVE THE GROUND.  THIS RESULTS IN HAVING ABOUT THREE TO FOUR GALLONS OF RETAIN PRODUCT REMAIN IN THE HOSE AFTER THE TRAILER COMPARTMENT IS EMPTY.  THE DRIVER PLACED ONE END OF HIS HOSE IN A FIVE GALLON BUCKET, THEN STARTED TO "WALK" (ROLL) HIS HOSE TOWARDS THE BUCKET TO EMPTY ITS CONTENTS.  HIS HOSE WAS TWISTED, SO, WHEN HE WAS NEAR THE BUCKET, THE HOSE STRAIGHTENED CAUSING THE BUCKET TO FLIP OVER SPILLING ITS CONTENTS.  THE DRIVER USED RAGS TO PRODUCT FORM THE ASPHALT. TO PREVENT FUTURE SPILLS, ALL DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO ASK FOR HELP, FOM THE CUSTOMER, TO DRAIN THEIR HOSE.  IT WOULD BE NECESSARY FOR THE CUSTOMER TO STEADY THE HOSE AND BUCKET WHILE THE DRIVER DRAINS HIS HOSE TOWARDS THE BUCKET.

DRIVER HAD EFFECTED DELIVERY ON E 25TH ST IN MINNEAPOLIS, MN.  CHECKED LOAD/ SECURED.  ENROUTE ON LAKE ST TO HWY 35 W ROAD WAS ROUGH AND DRIVER HEARED LAOD SHIFT AND PULL OVER TO CHECK.  ONE DEWARS WAS ON IT'S SIDE & HELIUM GAS WAS ESCAPING THROUGH THE PRESSURE ESCAPE VALVE.  DRIVER REPORTED VIA PHONE TO SERVICE CENTER & CITY WORKERS AT SCENE CALLED MINNEAPOLIS FIRE DEPT. WHICH RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY ALONG WITH THEIR HAZMAT UNIT.  THE EMERGENCY NUMBER ON LADING WAS CALLED & SHIPPER RESPONDED BY SENDING REPRESENTATIVE TO SITE.  MINNESOTA DOT DUTY OFFICER WAS ALSO NOTIFIED PER MN STATUTES.  NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER REPORT #174553.  MPLS FIRE DEPARTMENT BLOCKED OFF STEVENS AVE. BETWEEN LAKE ST & 31ST ST.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT UPON ARRIVAL OF SHIPPER REP. THAT VALVE WAS OKAY & TANK WAS UPRIGHTED & LOAD RESECURED.

column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING DRUM QUINTITIES OF HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CHEMDESIGN CORPORATION LOCATED AT 99 DEVELOPMENT ROAD IN FITCHBURG, MA TO ALLWORTH, INC LOCATED AT 101 SOUTH PARK AVE IN MT. PLEASANT, TN. THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE MADE A ROUTINE STOP AT A REST AREA LOCATED AT INTERSTATE 75 IN WALTON, KENTUCKY.  PRIOR TO DEPARTING FROM THE REST AREA, THE DRIVER COMPLETED A LOAD CHECK AT WHICH TIME HE NOTICED A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL (APPROXIMATELY 1-2 OUNCES) OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TRAILER ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT OF THE REST AREA.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY COVERED THE AREA WITH SPEEDI DRY AND CONTACTED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR TO REPORT THE INCIDENT.  AT THIS POINT, A FIELD SERVICE CREW WAS DISPATCHED FROM CLEAN HARBOR'S CINCINNATI, OH SERVICE CENTER.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, THE FIELD SERVICE CREW IDENTIFIED A PINHOLE LEAK IN THE SIDE OF THE CONTAINER AND OVERPACKED IT IN A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM. ALL SPILLED MATERIAL (1-2 OUNCES THAT ESCAPED FROM THE VAN TRAILER ALONG WITH THE 5 GALLONS OF MATERIAL CONTAINED WITHIN THE TRAILER) WAS ABSORBED WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED IN THE SALVAGE DRUM.  THE DRUM ALONG WITH ALL CLEANUP MATERIAL WAS SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO THE INTENDED DISPOSAL FACILITY IDENTIFIED ON THE SHIPPING PAPER.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED PRIOR TO LOADING AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED.  ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

column168: ON MAY 18, 1993, ON A ROUTINE DISPOSAL RUN FROM LAIDLAW (LA PORTE,TX) TOLAIDLAW (REIDSVILLE, N.C.) A SPILL OCCURRED AT THE UNION 76 TRUCK STOP IN GRANDBAY, ALABAMA, THE DRIVER, CHESTER RIOS, CALLED INSTRUCTED CHESTER TO CONTAINTHE SPILL AS BEST HE COULD AND INFORM THE TRUCK STOP REPRESENTATIVE OF THESITUATION. AT 4:45AM., CHESTER CALLED AGAIN TO LET ME KNOW THAT THE TRUCK STOPPERSONNEL HAD BEEN NOTIFIED AND THAT THE TRUCK HAD BEEN WAS THAN TOLD TO DETERMINE FROM A PH TEST OF THE LIQUID WHICH STREAM ON THE MANIFEST THIS COULDBE. CHESTER CALLED AGAIN TOT HE FACILITY AT 6:15AM TO LET ME KNOW THAT THESPILL WAS CONTAINED BY ADDING MORE ABSORBENT UNDERNEATH THAT THE TRUCK AND PAILPLACED UNDER THE LEAK FROM THE TRAILER. I CALLED THE OPERATION MANAGER, GARY BURNS TO LET HIM KNOW WHAT WAS GOING ON. I THEN CONTACTED LAIDLAW (BATON ROUGE,LA) TO ASK FOR ASSISTANCE IN REMEDIATING THE SPILL. THEY COULD ONLY AFFORD MEONE PERSON AND THEY ESTIMATED HIS DEPARTURE TIME TO BE 8:00AM, PUTTING HIS ARRIVAL TIME AT THE SCENE AROUND 11:00AM. WITH NO TRUCK AVAILABLE TO OFF-LOAD DRUMS FROM THE LEAKING TRAILER. I SET UP A RYDER RENTAL TRUCK IN MOBIL, ALABAMA THAT CHESTER RIOS COULD LATER PICK UP. RYDER CONFIRMED THIS AGREEMENT AT 7:15AM. ALL PROPER AUTHORITES FOR THE ALABAMA SPILL CONTINGENCY PLAN WERE NOTIFIEDBY THE TRUCK STOP REPRESENTATIVES AND WERE ENROUTE TO THE SCENE OF THE SPILL.AT 10:10AM AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS MOBILIZED FROM THE LA PORTE, TX.FACILITY DISPATCHED TO THE TRUCK STOP WITH ADDITIONAL SUPPLIES AND ANOTHERTRACTOR TRAILER. THEIR ESTIMATED TIME OF ARRIVAL AT 6:00PM. I DISCUSSED THETIME OF THEIR ARRIVAL WITH SCOTT BROWN, THE REPRESENTATIVE FROM THE ALABAMADEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT. AT THIS POINT, THE MAIN CONCERN WAS THEARRIVAL TIME OF THE CLEANUP CREW. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE ARRIVAL TIME WASNOT ACCEPTABLE AND THAT A QUICKER RESPONSE WAS NEEDED. REIDEL-PETERSONENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES OUT OF MOBILE, ALABAMA WAS CONTACTED AND A CLEANUP CREWWAS IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED TO THE TRUCK STOP AND THIS WAS CONFIRMED BY THEIRMOBIL OFFICE AT 12:15PM. THE REIDEL CREW REMEDIATED THE LEAKING DRUM ANDPERFORMED ALL THE NECESSARY CLEANUP WHICH TOOK APPROXIMATELY 4.5 HOURS. WHENTHE TRACTOR TRAILER COMING FROM OUR LA PORTE FACILITY ARRIVED, THE ENTIRE TRUCKWAS OFF-LOADED ONTO THIS NEW TRAILER AND WAS SCHEDULED TO CONTINUE ITS ROUTE.THE TRAILER THAT CONTAINED THE SPILL MATERIAL WAS REMEDIATED AND WASHED. THELAIDLAW PERSONNAL THEN NOTIFIED THE UNION 76 TRUCK STOP MANAGER, LOCAL FIREDEPARTMENT, AND SHERIFFS OFFICE TO CONFIRM THAT ALL NECESSARY PROCEDURES HADBEEN ACCOMPLISHED. THIS  WAS CONFIRMED AND THIS TRUCK WAS ALSO SENT ON ITS WAYENROUTE TO THE LA PORTE FACILITY.

DRIVER INSPECTED INTERIOR OF TRAINER AND NOTED A 55 GALLON POLY DRUM CONTAINING HYDROFLOUSILIC ACID CRACKED AND LEAKING.  THE DRUM HAD A VERTICAL CRACK FROM THE TOP OF THE DRUM DOWN THE SIDE TO WITHIN 10 INCHES OF THE BASE, THE CRACK EXTENDED HORIZONTALLY ABOUT 5 INCHES. THE CONTAINER WAS LOADED LOCKED IN THE TRAILER ADJACENT TO ANOTHER DRUM AND PALLET CONTAINING BAGGED PRODUCT.  NOTHING HAD STRUCK OR COME IN CONTACT WITH THE FAILED DRUM AND IT WAS STILL UPRIGHT.  THE DRUM WAS LAID ON IT'S SIDE TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE. THE DRIVER MADE MUD DIKES IN THE STREET GUTTER TO PREVENT RUN OFF OF MATERIAL DRIPPING FROM TRAILER. ASHLAND HAS A POLICY TO NOT FILL POLY DRUMS OVER 5 YEARS OLD.  THIS DRUM WAS PICKED UP AT A VENDOR JUST PRIOR TO THE INCIDENT.  AFTER THE INCIDENT WE NOTED THAT THE DRUM WAS OVER 5 YEARS OLD.  WE WILL STRESS TO OUR VENDORS THAT WE WILL NOT ACCEPT MATERIAL IN POLY DRUMS THAT ARE OVER 5 YEARS OLD.

column168: DRIVER PUT DROP PIPE IN TOP OF TANK WHEN PUMP WAS STARTED THE PIPE JUMPED OUT OF TOP OF TANK AND FELL ON THE GROUND.  HE SHUT DOWN THE PUMP AND PICKED UP THE HOSE. WHEN ARRIVING AT C.H. PATRICK IN GREENVILLE, SC (A CHEMICAL MANUFACTURER) OUR DRIVER NOTICED A LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE LEFT AND RIGHT FRONT CORNERS OF HIS TRAILER.  THE DRIVER BELIEVED THAT A PORTION OF HIS LOAD HAD SHIFTED WHILE IN TRANSIT.  A CLEANUP TEAM WAS CONTACTED TO UNLOAD THE TRAILER AND CLEANUP THE SPILL.  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A TOTE TANK LOADED ON THE TRAILER HAD SHIFTED AND THAT THE LEFT FRONT LEG OF THE TANK HAD PUNCTURED A STEEL DRUM LOADED IN FRONT OF THE TANK.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND ALL RESIDUE WAS PROCESSED THROUGH C. H. PATRICKS WASTE TREATMENT SYSTEM. OUR DRIVER HAS RECEIVED FURTHER INSTRUCTIONS IN THE USE OF BLOCKING AND BRACING, DUNNAGE, CARGO LOCKS, ETC.  WHICH WILL BE USED IN THE FUTURE TO PREVENT SIMILAR ACCIDENTS. . .

column168: FREIGHT CONTAINER PRMU-674243 WAS FOUND LEAKING ABOARD VESSEL MAYAGUEZ, VOYAGE 174-N.  CLEAR LIQUID WAS OBSERVED BENEATH DOORS AND FROM DECK ON FORWARD END.  LIQUID, UPON REACHING DECK, TURNED GREEN IN COLOR AND BLEACHED DECK WHITE.  ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS UTILIZED TO CONTROL AND CONFINE LEAK.  SHIPPER (EASTERN CHEMICAL WASTE SYTEMS) WAS CONTACTED AND EXPLAINED SPILLED MATERIAL WAS NON-HAZARDOUS AS PER GENERATOR'S DECLARATIONS. WHEN THE VESSEL ARRIVED ALL AUTHORITIES CONTACTED WERE PRESENT AND SHIPPER HAD A CREW WITH THE NECESSARY EQUIPMENT TO PERFORM CLEANING OPERATION ABOARD VESSEL AND FREIGHT CONTAINER.  LATER IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE MATERIAL CONTAINED IN 14 DRUMS AND MANIFESTED AS NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE RINSE WATER ACTUALLY CONTAINED HYDROCHLORIC ACID (MURIATIC ACID).  MATERIAL WAS SUPPOSED TO BE NEUTRALIZED BEFORE SHIPPING BY GENERATOR, CARIBE GENERAL ELECTRIC PRODUCTS, INC.  FOR UNKNOWN REASONS LIQUID WAS NOT NEUTRALIZED AND PACKAGED IN INADEQUATE METAL DRUMS.  THREE DRUMS WERE FOUND WITH NUMEROUS PIN HOLES CAUSED BY THE CONCENTRATED ACID. LIQUID ON LEAKING DRUMS WAS PUMPED INTO 55 GALLON PLASTIC DRUMS AND TAKEN TO CONSIGNEE'S FACILITIES.  BOTH SPILLED AREA ABOARD VESSEL AND FREIGHT CONTAINER WERE PROPERLY CLEANED BY SHIPPER/CONSIGNEE.  NO FATALITIES OR INJURIES WERE REPORTED AS A CONSEQUENCE OF INCIDENT.  AUTHORITIES IN ATTENDANCE DURING INCIDENT: 1. MARYLAND DEPT OF ENVIRONMENT, 2. FBI ENVIRONMENTAL CRIMES DIV., 3. BALTIMORE CITY FIRE DEPT., 4. US COAST GUARD, 5. MD PORT ADMINISTRATION, 6. ITO.  REPRESENTATIVES FROM THE FOLLOWING COMPANIES WERE ALSO IN ATTENDANCE: 1. PR MARINE MANAGEMENT, INC., 2. EASTERN CHEMICAL WASTE SYSTEMS, INC., 3. INTL CARGO SURVEYORS, INC

column168: THE CONTAINER WAS PART OF THE INBOUND FREIGHT LOAD BEING TRANSPORTED FROM LAX TO THE FEDERAL EXPRESS FACILITY IN CANOGA PARK. THE FREIGHT LOAD WAS ISOLATED AND SPILL CLEAN UP WAS BEGUN ACCORDING TO ESTABLISHED PROCEDURES. APPARENTLY THE BOTTOM OF THE CAN FAILED RESULTING IN THE SPILL.  THERE WERE NO OUTSIDE ELEMENTS THAT COULD HAVE CAUSED THE FAILURE NOR WAS IT DROPPED IN HANDLING.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN OUR APPROVED DISPOSAL DRUM.  THE RECIPIENT WAS CONTACTED AND THEY INDICATED THAT THEY STILL WANTED THE COMMODITY.  THE RECIPIENT MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO PICK UP THE PACKAGE AND WAS RELEASED TO THEM ON 05/05/93.

column168: VEHICLE WAS CONTINUTING TRIP AFTER A STOP AT THE TULSA, OK BRANCH OF VAN WATERS & ROGERS INC. AND WAS TAKING FOUR (4) DRUMS OF WASTE SYSTECH ENVIRONMENTAL CORP., FREDONIA, KS. DRUMS WERE NOT LEAKING UPON DEPARTURE FROM VW & R, TULSA, OK.  WHEN UNIT HAD TRAVELED APPROXIMATELY SIXTY (60) MILES TO KANAS BORDER WEIGH STATION, KANSAS HIGHWAY PATROL PERFORMED DRIVE/VEHICLE EXAMINATION AND IT WAS AT THIS TIME THAT SEEPAGE WAS COMING FROM THE LOWER SIDE OF ONE DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS TURNED ON ITS SIDE TO PREVENT ADDITIONAL SPILLAGE.  A RECOVERY DRUM WAS DISPATCHED FROM VW&R TULSA, OK AND WHEN IT ARRIVED, LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED INSIDE, DRUM WAS SECURED, MARKED, AND LABELED AND UNIT DEPARTED TO SYSTECH ENVIRONMENTAL CORP. WHERE ALL WAS ACCEPTED PER MANIFEST.  THESE DRUMS HAD BEEN INSPECTED ON AT LEAST 3 SEPARATE OCCASIONS WHILE IN THE POSSESSION OF VW&R WITH NO EVIDENCE  OF LEAKAGE AT ANY OF THOSE INSPECTIONS. IN THE FUTURE AN OVERPAK DRUM WITH PPE & ABSORBENTS WILL BE CARRIED ON OR IN THE TRAILER TRANSPORTING HAZARDOUS WASTE.

column17: HUNT J B SPECIAL COMMODITIES I
column168: THIS INCIDENT OCCURED AT NORTHWEST INTERNATIONAL, A TRUCK DEALER IN EAU CLAIRE WI.  OUR TRAILER #231 WAS LOADED AT WASTE RESEARCH & RECLAMATION CO., INC. LOCATED AT 5200 STATE ROAD 93, EAU CLAIRE, WI.  THE DRIVER WENT TO NORTHWEST INTERNATIONAL TO HAVE REPAIRS MADE TO HIS TRUCK AND UNCOUPLED THE TANK ON THE PARKING LOT.  THE DOME LID ON THE REAR OF THE TANK WAS NOT COMPLETELY TIGHTENED AND ALLOWED APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF MATERIAL TO LEAK FROM THE TRAILER ONTO THE PARKING LOT.  THE TRAILER MUST HAVE BEEN COMPLETELY FULL FOR THIS TO HAVE HAPPENED.  THE DRIVER UPON DISCOVERING THIS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED WASTE RESEARCH & RECLAMATION, WHO DISPATCHED A CREW TO THE SCENE.  THE DRIVER THEN NOTIFIED MYSELF AND REPORTED THE INCIDENT.  I COMPLETED OUR "HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPILL INCIDENT REPORT" WHICH I USED TO MAKE THE NOTIFICATION TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER. JIM MERTES WITH THE WR & R CREW CALLED ME AND REPORTED THAT ALL THE SPILL MATERIAL HAD BEEN REMOVED FROM THE PARKING LOT AND THAT IT AND THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS WOULD BE RETURNED TO WASTE RESEARCH & RECLAMATION FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  THERE WAS NO THREAT TO HUMANS OR TO THE ENVIRONMENT BECAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT.  DRIVERS HAVE BEEN CAUTIONED TO ALWAYS CHECK ALL TANK CLOSURES, DOME LIDS AND VALVES BEFORE MOVING THE CARGO TANK.  WASTE RESEARCH & RECLAMATION WAS MADE AWARE THAT OVERFILLING THIS TRAILER AND NOT TIGHTENING THE DOME LIDS AFTER LOADING CONTRIBUTED TO THIS ACCIDENT.

column168: WHEN SUPERVISOR AND UNLOADER OPENED DOOR ON TRAILER THE ODOR WAS NOTICED IMMEDIATELY.  THEN NOTICED THE SMOKING PACKAGE. RECOMMEND THAT NO. 1 THE SHIPPER SHOULD LABEL HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AS SUCH AND HAVE THE LIDS SECURED SOMEHOW.  ALSO NEED TO HAVE PACKING LINING TO PREVENT LEAKAGE FROM THE BOX IF AN INNER SPILL SHOULD OCCUR.

column168: PACKAGE WAS PART OF INBOUND FREIGHT LOAD INTO THE PORTSMOUTH STATION.  THE PACKAGE WAS BLOCKED AND BRACED IN A FREIGHT CONTAINER LOADED INTO THE VEHICLE.  WHEN THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE STATION HE TOOK THE DOORS OFF OF THE FREIGHT CONTAINER.  AT THIS POINT HE NOTICED AN ODOR IN THE CONTAINER AS HE STARTED TO UNLOAD THE CONTAINER.  HE ISOLATED THE PACKAGE WHERE THE ODOR APEARED TO BE COMING FROM.  UPON CLOSER EXAMINATION OF THE CONTENTS ONE OF THE CANS HAD SEEPAGE INTO THE PACKAGING MATERIAL WHICH THE MATERIAL COMPLETELY ABSORBED.  THE CONTAINER WAS REWRAPPED TO AVOID FURTHER LEAKAGE, REPACKAGED IN ITS ORIGINAL CONTAINER AND FORWARDED TO THE RECIPIENT.

AT APPROX 7:00AM IT WAS BROUGHT TO MY ATTENTION BY THE UNLOADER THAT THERE WAS A PACKAGE LEAKING ON THE REAR OF THE TRAILER (#296520).  AT THAT TIME I INSTRUCTED THE UNLOADER TO MOVE OVER TO THE NEXT TRAILER.  AT THAT TIME I PLACED THE PACKAGE INTO A SPILL CONTAINER.  I MOVED THE PACKAGE TO AN OPEN AREA AND INSPECTED IT AFTER CONSULTING THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPPING GUIDE AND RESPONSE GUIDE.  I FOUND THAT ALL FOUR CONTAINERS HAD LOOSE CAPS, WHICH CAUSED THE LEAKAGE.  I ALSO FOUND THAT THE UN1903 DID NOT MATCH THE PROPER DOT SHIPPING NAME.

column25: ANKO PRODUCTS CO OF TEXAS INC
column168: WHILE OUR DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO MAKE HIS DELIVERY CONSIGNEE ASKED HIM TO LAY THE DRUM ON ITS SIDE TO UNLOAD SINCE HE DID NOT HAVE A PALLET AVAILABLE.  WHEN THE DRIVER STARTED TO LEAN THE DRUM OVER, THE WEIGHT SHIFTED AND HE WAS UNABLE TO KEEP IT FROM SLIDING DOWN ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  WHEN IT DID THE BUNG (LID) POPPED OFF AND THE LIQUID SPLASHED ON HIM.  THE DRIVER WAS IMMEDIATELY HOSED DOWN AND BROUGHT TO THE HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION AND RELEASED.  DRIVER HAS BEEN INSTRUCTED NOT TO TRY THIS TYPE OF UNLOADING PROCEDURE AGAIN.

column168: ALTHOUGH THE AMOUNT LOSS WAS VERY MINIMAL I FEEL THAT A RECORD SHOULD BE KEPT.  AS I MENTIONED ONLY ABOUT 4 OZ WAS LOST OUT OF A 1 GALLON CAN BUT THE FUMES WERE ENOUGH TO CAUSE THE DRIVER TO BECOME NAUSIATED AND WAS SENT TO THE HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION AND RELEASED.  HE REMAINED OFF WORK FOR THREE DAYS AND RETURNED AND BECAME ILL AGAIN.  HE IS STILL OFF WORK BUT IS GOING TO THE DOCTOR FOR MORE TESTING.  WE AT SAIA ASSUME RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE DAMAGED CARTON.  THROUGH IMPROPER BLOCKING AND PROTECTION.  AS NOTED EARLIER THE LID ON ONE OF THE CANS POPPED OFF WHEN THE OTHER FREIGHT HIT THE SIDE OF THE CARTON.  CONSIGNEE IS AWARE OF THIS INCIDENT AND MENTIONED THAY THEY HAVE NEVER HAD A PROBLEM WITH THE PRODUCT BEFORE. THIS COULD HAVE BEEN RELATED TO THE FACT THAT THE LEAK TOOK PLACE INSIDE A CLOSED TRAILER WHERE VENTILATION WAS NOT AVAILABLE.

FLATBED TRUCK CONTAINING 7 FULL 1 TON CHLORINE CONTAINERS AND 4 EMPTY 1 TON CONTAINERS WAS STOPPED FOR A TRAFFIC LIGHT ON A STEEP HILL.  WHEN THE LIGHT CHANGED, THE DRIVER STARTED FORWARD. THE SUPPORTS HOLDING THE CONTAINERS ON THE TRUCK FAILED AND THE CONTAINERS ROLLED OFF THE TRUCK AND DOWN THE HILL CAUSING DAMAGE TO 1 CAR, 2 VANS AND 1 TRUCK.  ALL THE DAMAGED VEHICLES WERE PARKED AND UNOCCUPIED.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND NO CHLORINE WAS RELEASED.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AS A PRECUATION EVACUATED A TWO BLOCK AREA AND CLOSED DOWN THE STREET TO TRAFFIC.  DELTA CHEMICAL CORPORATION EMPLOYEES RESPONDED AND WITH THE USE OF A CRAIN WERE ABLE TO PLACE THE CONTAINERS BACK ON THE TRUCK.  THE SUPPORTS WERE REPAIRED AND THE TRUCK RETURNED TO THE PLACE OF ORIGIN.  THE STREET WAS CLOSED FROM 0700 - 1500 HR.

column168: A STRAIGHT VACUUM TRUCK WAS DISPATCHED TO ORGANIC TECHNOLOGIES LOCATED AT 4654 KENNY RD IN COLUMBUS, OH IN ORDER TO PICK UP A LOAD OF HAZARDOUS WASTE LIQUID, N.O.S. CONTAINING TOLUENE AND ACETONE.  THIS VEHICLE WAS THEN SENT TO SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC.  WHERE THE MATERIAL WAS TO BE TRANSFERRED INTO A SECOND TRANSPORT VEHICLE FOR CONTINUING TRANSPORTATION TO A DESTINATION FACILITY.  UPON ARRIVAL AT SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC., FACILITY PERSONNEL ALONG WITH THE DRIVER OF THE VACUUM TRUCK SET UP THE TRANSFER HOSE BETWEEN THE TWO VEHICLES IN PREPARATION FOR THE PUMPING OPERATION.  UPON COMMENCEMENT OF THE PUMPING, THE INITIAL PRESSURE SURGE THROUGH THE TRANSFER HOSE CAUSED THE HOSE TO POP OUT OF THE TOP DOME HATCH SPILLLING APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF MATERIAL ONTO THE CONTAINMENT AREA OF THE FACILITY.  THE OPERATION WAS IMMEDIATELY HALTED AND THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED WITH SPEEDI DRY WHICH WAS CONTAINERIZED AND DISPOSED OF THROUGH A FULLY LICENSED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY.  PLEASE NOTE THAT THE ABOVE DESCRIBED RELEASE WAS NOT CAUSED BY A CONTAINER FAILURE AND SECTION VIII OF THE ENCLOSED DOT F 5800.1 REFLECTS THIS.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, ALL FACILITY PERSONNEL RESPONSIBLE FOR MATERIAL TRANSFERS HAVE BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED IN THE PROPER PROCEDURES REQUIRED TO TRANSFER MATERIAL FROM ONE TANK TO ANOTHER.  IN ADDITION, ALL TRANSFERS WILL BE CONDUCTED THROUGH VALVES RATHER THAN THROUGH THE DOME HATCH WHEREVER PRACTICAL.  IN THE EVENT THE TRANSFER MUST BE CONDUTED THROUGH THE DOME HATCH, ALL HOSES WILL BE SECURED IN POSITION TO PREVENT THE HOSE FROM COMING OUT OF THE DOME HATCH.

DAMAGED CARTON TRANSFERRED TO OS&D FOR FURTHER HANDLING.  DOCK PERSONNEL MUST ENSURE THAT LIQUID HAZARDOUS MATERIAL IS LOADED ACCORDING TO THE DIRECTIONAL ARROWS ON THE CARTON.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING DRUM QUANTITIES OF HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE, MASSACHUSETTS TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND, INC. LOCATED AT CLEVELAND, OHIO.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE DESTINATION FACILITY, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A PINHOLE LEAK HAD DEVELOPED AT THE BOTTOM EDGE OF THE CONTAINER THAT CAUSED APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF MATERIAL TO LEAK ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY OVERPACKED THE CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM AND ABSORBED THE RELEASED  MATERIAL WITH SPEEDI DRY.  ALL SPILL CLEAN-UP MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN THE SALVAGE DRUM AND AND DISPOSED OF THROUGH CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND, INC. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED PRIOR TO LOADING AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED.  ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

column168: EMPLOYEE WAS LOADING A 16 GALLON DRUM OF WASTE MINERAL SPIRITS ONTO THE TRUCK BY LIFTING THE DRUM BY THE LOCK RING WHICH SEALS THE CONTAINER'S LID.  THE LOCK RING WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED, AND AS HE LIFTED THE DRUM, THE DRUM, THE LID AND RING POPPED OFF, CAUSING THE DRUM TO SPILL ON THE LOT WHICH WAS PAVED WITH ASPHALT.  FOUR GALLONS OF SPILLED WASTE WAS CONTAINED ON THE LOT AND COMPLETELY RECOVERED USING GROUND CORN COB ABSORBENT.  SPILL RESIDUE WAS DRUMMED, LABELED, AND TRANSPORTED TO A SAFETY-KLEEN RECYCLE CENTER FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  TOOLS USED IN CLEAN UP, BROOM, SHOVEL, ETC. WERE DECONTAMINATED USING SOAP AND WATER.  WASH WATER WAS DRUMMED, ALONG WITH THE OTHER SPILL MATERIAL.  THE SPILL KITS WERE RESTOCKED.  PROPER DRUM HANDLING PROCEDURES WERE REVIEWED WITH THE RESPONSIBLE EMPLOYEE TO PREVENT FUTURE OCCURANCES.

DRIVER HAD TO UNLOAD PRODUCT INTO TWO STORAGE TANKS.  WHEN HE HAD THE FIRST TANK ALMOST FULL THE DRIVER HAD TO SWITCH VALVES TO THE 2ND TANK. IN THE PROCESS OF SWITCHING VALVES FROM ONE TANK TO THE OTHER, VALVES LOCKED TOGETHER, CAUSING THE FIRST TANK TO OVER FILL.  AS SOON AS THE DRIVER NOTICED FUEL COMING OUT THE TOP HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE PUMP. PROPER PROCEDURE WOULD HAVE BEEN TO TURN OFF THE PUMP BEFORE SWITCHING THE VALVES FROM THE 2ND TANK.  THIS DRIVER WORKS FOR AN OWNER OPERATOR, THE OWNER OPERATOR HAS TERMINATED THE DRIVER FOR NOT USING PROPER UNLOADING PROCEDURES.

WHILE INSPECTING CARS IN WARREN YARD, CAR INSPECTORS NOTICED A SLIGHT DRIP FROM ONE OF THE INTERIOR HEATER COIL OUTLETS ON A CAR PLACARDED UN 1760 RESIDUE.  IT IS SUSPECTED THAT AS THE SUN WARMED THE TANK SHELL, THE PRESSURE INCREASED CAUSING THE MATERIAL TO BE FORCED INTO THE HEATER COIL. WHEN THE CAR COOLED, THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE LEAKING MATERIAL WAS CAUGHT AND CONTAINED IN A BUCKET AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.  THERE WERE NO ENVIRONMENTAL CONCERNS AND NO OUTSIDE EMERGENCY ASSISTANCE WAS REQUIRED. THE CAR IS BEING HELD IN THE WARREN YARD UNTIL AN EMERGENCY EXEMPTION AUTHORITY IS RECEIVED FROM THE DOT.  UPON RECEIPT OF THE EXEMPTION, THE CAR WILL BE SHIPPED TO RESCAR, IN DUBOIS, PENNSYLVANIA FOR REPAIRING A DEFECTIVE HEATER COIL.

THE CARTON ONLY CONTAINED THE MARKINGS "CAUTION, PRECISION INSTRUMENT HANDLE WITH EXTREME CARE.  MUST NOT BE DROPPED".  THE DRIVER REPORTED THE INCIDENT AND WAS DIRECTED TO THE NEAREST MEDICAL FACILITY BY THE DISPATCHER OF HIS COMPANY (COLMA DRAYAGE).  THE SHIPPER OF THE LIQUID (MARTEC MARINE) WAS ALSO NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AND REQUESTED TO TAKE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO AVOID FUTURE OCCURRANCES OF THIS NATURE.  AN FAA SPECIAL AGENT, ANNMARIE LONTZ, CONDUCTED AN ONSITE INVESTIGATION OF THE MATERIAL TO INCLUDE TAKING PHOTOGRAPHS OF THE MATERIAL AND THE PACKAGING.

column168: REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION, D.L. WHITELEY WAS NOTIFIED BY T.L. MILLER, MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS, HINKLE YARD, THAT TANK CAR PROX 41138 WAS LEAKING MATERIAL FROM AROUND TOP OF TANK CAR.  WHITELEY RESPONDED AND FOUND GASKET MANWAY COVER DEFECTIVE, AND NOTED TANK CAR HAD BEEN OVER FILLED ACCOUNT PRODUCT WAS INTO MANWAY NOZZLE AND PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM TANK CAR FROM AROUND DEFECTIVE GASKET AND THROUGH VACUUM RELIEF VALVE. INSPECTION DEVELOPED THAT ONE OF EIGHT MANWAY COVER SWING BOLTS WAS DISENGAGED AND HANGING DOWN, THREE OF EIGHT WERE ENGAGED; HOWEVER, REQUIRED SEVERAL TURNS BEFORE COMING IN CONTACT WITH MANWAY COVER, FOUR OF EIGHT ENGAGED AND AGAINST MANWAY COVER BUT NOT WRENCH TIGHT.  MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND IN GOOD ORDER.  PROPERLY SECURED MANWAY COVER PLATE.  CLARK KING, AMOCO CANADA, AND GEORGE FOSTER, CRYSEN REFINING, WERE FURNISHED DETAILS.

column168: MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY (MCTS) REEDER WAS NOTIFIED THAT A TRAILER WITH DRUMS HAD SHIFTED AND BROKEN OPEN THE REAR DOORS. THE DRUMS WERE LYING ON THE FLATCAR AND WERE LEAKING.  THE TRAILER DISPLAYED A CORROSIVE PLACARD.  MCTS REEDER RESPONDED AND UPON ARRIVAL FOUND FIVE DRUMS LYING ON THE FLATCAR, FOUR OF WHICH WERE LEAKING.  FURTHER INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THREE OF THE DRUMS HAD BEEN FOUND BETWEEN TRACKS SIX AND SEVEN IN IN SETTEGAST.  LLOYD SMITH AND CREW HAD PLACED THE DRUMS BACK ON THE FLATCAR.  EMTECH ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTRACTED TO OVERPACK THE DAMAGED AND LEAKING DRUMS.  THE TRAILER WAS MOVED TO THOMPSON CARGO SERVICE FOR REWORKING.  THE DAMAGED DRUMS WILL BE HANDLED PER THE SHIPPER'S ORDERS.  EMTECH CLEANED THE FLATCAR AND THE CONTAMINATED SOIL ACCORDING TO THE SHIPPERS INSTRUCTIONS.  T. JACKSON OF CHEMTREC AND SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

SPECIAL AGENT/HAZMAT (SA/HM) B. BALLANCE WAS NOTIFIED BY REG. MGR B STINE THAT A LEAKING TRAILER WAS NOTED AT UP MOTOR FREIGHT.  SA/HM BALLANCE RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT CONTAINER TOLU 943000 ON FLATCAR TTWX 981450 WAS LEAKING SODIUM BISULPHITE NEAR THE SEAM AT REAR BASE OF THE CONTAINER.  SOME PRODUCT WAS ALSO ON THE DECK OF THE FLATCAR.  SA/HM BALLANCE CONTACTED THE SHIPPER HYDRITE CHEMICALS AND SPOKE WITH LYNN TESS. CONTACT WAS ALSO MADE WITH THE CONSIGNEE CORN PRODUCTS.  CONSIGNEE AGREED TO ACCEPT THE LOAD IMMEDIATELY.  CA TANK LINERS ESCORTED THE CONTAINER TO CORN PRODUCTS AND UNLOADED.  CAR WAS REMOVED FROM SERVICE PENDING INSPECTION.  STOCKTON FIRE DEPARTMENT AND APPROPRIATE AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: SPECIAL AGENT/HAZMAT (SA/HM) D. WOMACK WAS NOTIFIED BY SENIOR SPECIAL AGT. J. HERRING THAT UPRR HAD DELIVERED TANK CAR ECDX 812104 TO THE KCS RAILROAD, MALLIN INTERCHANGE YARD.  INSPECTOR DUNCAN OF THE U.S. DEPT. OF TRANSPORTATION FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION HAD NOTED THE CAR LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET AT APPROXIMATELY FIVE DROPS PER MINUTE.  SSA HERRING NOTIFIED THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, LA DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENT. QUALITY, LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONDERS AND CHEMTREC. UPON ARRIVAL, SA HM WOMACK MET WITH SSA HERRING, DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY AGENT B. LAMBIGHT, AND FRA INSPECTOR DUNCAN.  STATE POLIC TROOPER F. FRONTENOT AND SSA HERRING WERE ABLE TO SECURE LEAK BY TURNING THE TOP OPERATED VALVE OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET, TWO AND ONE HALF TURNS.  THEN BY TIGHTING THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP BY THREE QUARTER OF A TURN.  SEAL "ETHYL PETRO ADD.  40808" WAS REMOVED IN ORDER TO SECURE THIS CAR AND SEAL "UP D  836128" WAS APPLIED UPON SECUREMENT.  SA/HM MET WITH KCS TRAINMASTER E. G. CARTER AT MALLIN INTERCHANGE YARD AND INFORMED HIM THAT LEAK WAS SECURED AND THE CAR RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.  CAR WAS THEN ACCEPTED FOR INTERCHANGE.  SA/HM WOMACK CONTACTED M. LYNCH OF ETHYL PETROLEUM ADDITIVES, 504-338-8629, AND INFORMED HIM OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: ON 051793 AT APPROXIMATELY 1015AM THE ANGLETON SWITCH CREWS NOTICED THE ABOVE CAR LEAKING FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED.  THEY NOTIFIED MMM WITT WHO THEN NOTIFIED REEDER.  UPON ARRIVAL, REEDER FOUND THE TOP OF THE CAR DRY AND NO SIGN OF LEAKAGE.  OPENING THE MANWAY COVER, REEDER DISCOVERED THE O-RING ON THE VACUUM RELIEF DEVICE AS NOT SEATED PROPERLY.  AFTER WORKING WITH THE O-RING REEDER WAS ABLE TO GET IT SEALED, HOWEVER, IT APPEARS TO BE THE WRONG SEAL.  REEDER ALSO FOUNG THE AIR VALAVE WAS NOT WRENCH TIGHT. THE PLUG IN THE LIQUID LINE WAS LOOSE.  BOTH PROBLEMS WERE CORRECTED. AFTER REPAIRS WERE COMPLETE, WITT SHOOK THE CAR.  NO LEAKS WERE FOUND. REEDER REMOVED AIR PRODUCTS SEALS 50925 AND 509261.  THEY WERE REPLACED WITH MPRR 17-169082 AND MPRR 17-169076.  REEDER CONTACTED FIELDSON AT AIR PRODUCTS.  FIELDSON REPORTED THIS WAS THE FIRST TRIP FOR THIS CAR SINCE BEING SHOPPED FOR IT'S ANNUAL INSPECTION.  J. BOTWINCIK OF CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

INSPECTION DEVELOPED ONE OF SIX MANWAY COVERS SWING BOLTS WAS DISENGAGED HANGING DOWN, TWO OTHERS WERE LOOSE AND COULD BE DISENGAGED BY HAND WITHOUT ANY EFFORT, THE OTHER THREE WERE WRENCH TIGHT.  OPENED COVER PLATE AND NOTED THE GASKET WAS IN GOOD CONDITION AND CAR HAD 11 INCHES OF OUTAGE.  PROPERLY SECURED COVER PLATE AND RELEASED CAR FOR CONTINUED TRANSPORTATION.  ALSO NOTED THE STUFFING BOX COVER ON THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS MISSING.  ALSO THE OPERATING ROD WAS NOT ATTACHED TO THE VALVE AS IT TURNED FREELY AND COULD BE RAISED UP OUT OF CAR. DISCUSSED EXCEPTIONS WITH SHIPPER WHO INDICATED CAR WOULD BE REPAIRED AFTER BEING MADE EMPTY.  T. FLORES OF CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Hose; Loading or Unloading Lines; Piping or Fittings
column168: DRIVER, MARK GALLAGHER, ARRIVED AT BIOKYOWA AT APPROXIMATELY 0630 ON 05/31/93. HE BEGAN PRESSURIZING THE TANK AS HE WAS GETTING SET UP AND HAD ABOUT 15 PSI IN TANK.  HE WENT TO TAKE THE CAP OFF OF THE OUTLET VALVE ON THE TRAILER AND PULLED THE EAR OF CAP. IT BEGAN TO LEAK SO HE CLOSED THE CAP AND RECHECKED TO MAKE SURE THE VALVE WAS CLOSED, IT WAS.  HE TRIED TO OPEN THE CAP, PULLED ON EAR AND HAD NO LEAKAGE.  HE PULLED THE OTHER EAR AND THE CAP BLEW OFF.  THE EMERGENCY VALVE WAS OPEN AND THE HOSE WAS NOT HOOKED UP.  DRIVER HAD SOME CONTACT WITH THE HCL BUT WASHED OFF WITH WATER HOSE.  HANDLE ON VALVE HAD TO BE PULLED ABOUT FOUR TIMES TO GET IT SHUT OFF AND STOP LEAKING.  APPROXIMATELY 5,060 POUNDS OF HCL WERE LOST ON THE GROUND.

ON 05/11/93 AT APPROXIMATELY 0302 HRS, I, KAREN NICHOLS/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR AT ABX, AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH 45177, INVESTIGATED A SHIPMENT BROUGHT TO MY ATTENTION BY DAN DUTIEL/SORT SUPV.  THE SHIPMENT WAS LEAKING A CLEAR LIQUID WITH THE ODOR OF RUBBING ALCOHOL.  I FOUND 1 FIBREBOARD BOX WITH NO HAZARD MARKINGS OR LABELS, NOR WERE THERE ANY SHIPER'S CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THE SHIPMENT.  THERE WERE NO ORIENTATION MARKINGS ON THE FIBREBOARD BOX.  INSIDE THE FIBREBOARD BOX I FOUND THE ITEMS LISTED BELOW: 1 X 22 OUNCE PLASTIC BOTTLE WITH A PUMP SPRAY NOZZLE.  THE OUTSIDE OF THE BOTTLE WAS MARKED "ISOPRO".  1 X 22 OUNCE BOTTLE WITH A PUMP SPRAY NOZZLE.  THE OUTSIDE OF THE BOTTLE WAS MARKED "DIH20".  3 X 10 OUNCE PLASTIC BOTTLES WITH PLASTIC SCREW-TYPE CLOSURE..1 MARKED "1,143 (MICRO)S STANDARD SOLUTION". 1 MARKED "12,880 (MICRO)S STANDARD SOLUTION". 1 MARKED "84 (MICRO)S STANDARD SOLUTION".  3 X 16 OUNCE BOTTLES WITH SCREW-TYPE CLOSURES.  CLOSURES HAVE FLIP-UP SPOUTS.  EACH MARKED "STANDARD BUFFER SOLUTION..."  (1) 1 - PH 7.00 PLUS OR MINUS 0.01 AT 20 DEGREES C".  (2) 1 - PH 4.00 PLUS OR MINUS 0.02 AT 20 DEGREES C".  (3) 1 - PH 10.00 PLUS OR MINUS 0.02 AT 20 DEGREES C".  1 X 600 FT ROPE.  150 X 3 OZ PLASTIC DRINK CUPS.  1 LARGE REEL OF MEASURING TAPE.  PH DETECTION INSTRUMENT.  2 PLASTIC DRUM LIDS.  THERE WERE NO HAZARD MARKINGS OR LABELS ON ANY OF THE INNER PACKAGINGS.  THIS SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD UNDER LOCK AND KEY IN OUR HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.

column62: Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1340 HOURS ON MAY 3, 1993, YARD CREW #4 AT CONWAY YARD DISCOVERED CONTAINER UFCU 394080 ON FLAT TTXX982015 LEAKING.  THE CONTAINER WAS LOADED WITH 72, 55 GALLON DRUMS CONTAINING DIETHYLHYDROXIYLAMINE, DESCRIBED AS A FLAMMABLE LIQUID, N.O.S.  PAUL ZOTTOLA, CONRAIL-ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, BUREA OF EXPLOSIVES INSPECTOR T. MANNAS AND PETRO-CLAN OF CARNEGIE, PA.  TO ACCOMPLISH TRANSFER AND REMOVAL OF FAULTY DRUM AND EFFECT CLEANUP OF THE CONTAINER.  ALL DEFECTIVE RUMS WERE N THE BOTTOM LAYER.  AS THE DRUMS WERE REMOVED THEY WERE PLACED ONT A PLASTIC AREA TO CONTAIN ANY LEAKING MATERIAL AND EXAMINED.  THE POSITIONS OF THE LEAKING DRUMS WERE (NOSE OF CONTAINER AS REFERENCE:  DRUM NUMBER 1 IN LEFT CORNER AND DRUM NUMBER 4 IN RIGHT CORNER):  THE 63RD M 55TH, & 39TH DRUMS WERE LEAKING.  THE DRUMS HAD BEEN PUNCTURED BY SCREWS PROTRUDING FROM THE WOODEN FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER.  THE 21ST DRUM WAS GOUGED BUT NOT PUNCTURED.  ALL DAMAGED DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED IN SALVAGE DRUMS.  ALL PROTRUDING FLOOR SCREWS WERE REMOVED.  THE ABSORBENT MATERIALS, ETC., WERE REMOVED CLEANED FROM THE CONTAINER AND FLAT CAR BY PERTO-CLEAN & PLACED IN SALVAGE DRUMS.  ALL SALVAGE DRUMS WERE PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED BY PERTO-CLEAN.  ONE-HALF INCH PARTICLE BOARD WAS PLACED ON THE FLOOR BETWEEN THE TOP & BOTTOM LAYERS THE CONTAINER DOORS WERE CLOSED, THE CONATINER REPOSITIONED ON FLAT CAR AND AUTHORIZED FOR TRANSPORTATION AT APPROXIMATELY 4:30 PM, 5-4-93.

ALL BUT 1200 GALLONS OF THE GASOLINE WAS BURNT, THE 1200 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WAS VACUUMED UP ALONG WITH 25 TONS OF SOIL THAT WAS AFFECTED. CLEAN UP OPERATION WAS PERFORMED BY CLEAN HARBORS INC.  ALL CONTAMINATION WAS RECOVERED UNDER THE DIRECTION OF MR. ROBET SWANN STATE OF MARYLAND DEPARTMENT OF THE ENVIRONMENT.

ON MAY 28, 1993 AT ABOUT 4:30 PM., OUR DRIVER HENRY HENNING WAS DELIVERING 4500 GALLONS OF #2 DIESEL FUEL TO THE CITY OF JANESVILLE, WISCONSIN GARAGE.  HE PULLED UP IN FORNT OF 2 ABOVE GROUND TANKS THAT WERE PULLY PLUMBED AND LABELED FOR PRODUCT.  ONE TANK WAS LABELED IN BLUE BACKGROUND MID GRAD UNLEAED AND THE OTHER IN BRIGHT YELLOW BACKGROUND DIESEL.  THESE SIGNS WERE BOTH APPROXIMATELY 20" X 20" SQUARE. NO OTHER ABOVE OR UNDER GROUND TANKS MARKED AT ALL ON THE PREMISES.  MR. HENNING LOOKED THE AREA OVER WILL AND HOOKED UP THE TANK MARKED DIESEL AND BEGAN TO UNLOAD.  THIS TANK HAS A 6" RETAINING WALL AROUND IT.  OUR DRIVER CONTINUED TO WATCH THE UNLOADING PROCEDURE, LOOKING OVER THE WALL REGULARY.  AFTER SEVERAL HUNDRED GALLONS OF DIESEL WERE UNLOADED INTO THIS TANK, IT BEGAN TO LEAK OUT OF A PATCH ON ITS SIDE.  AT THAT TIME, OUR DRIVER NOTICED IT IMMEDIATELY, STOPPED UNLOADING AND TRIED TO REVERSE THE PUMP TO PUT THE PRODUCT BACK INTO THE TRAILER.  HOWEVER, A CHECK VALVE IN THE PLUMBING PREVENTED ANY BACK FLOW.  WE HAD THE CHECK VALVE REMOVED AND PUMPED DOWN THE TANK. MEANWHILE, ABOUT 850 ALLONS LEAKED OUT AND INTO THE GROUND. WE NOTIFIED SEVEREAL PEOPLE OF THE INCIDENT.  AFTER TALKING TO THE CITY OF JANESVILLE, WE FOUND OUT THIS TANK WAS CONDEMNED ABOUT 2 YEARS AGO (OUT OF SERVICE) AND THE PROPERTY WAS PREVIOUSLY POLLUTED.  MONITORING WELLS WERE INSTALLED IN THE FALL OF 1992.  WE FEEL THAT THIS TANK SHOULD HAVE BEEN MADE IMMEDIATELY OUT OF SERVICE AND INOPERABLE WHEN CONDEMNED AND REMOVED SOON AFTER THAT.

TANK CAR REPORTED TO SLOSH FROM TOP WHEN MOVED AT SCX RAIL YARD IN RICHMOND, VA.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.  CSX CALLED MR BILL OERTLY. BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES, TO RESPOND.  OERTLY FOUND CAR TO HAVE A BLOWN RUPTURE DISK.  HE REPLACED THE DISK, SECURED THE CAR AND IT WAS RELEASED.

column168: AGENT H. WILLIAMS NOTIFIED MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY (MCTS) C. HILL THAT CAR UTLX 14009 WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP.  MCTS HILL RESPONDED AND INSPECTED DETERMINED THAT THE 2" PIPE HOLDING THE SAFETY VENT HAD BROKEN ABOUT 6" ABOVE TANK CAR.  MCTS HILL ACCOMPAINED BY MANAGER MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE (MMM) D. RANKINS, RE-THREADED THE 2" PIPE AND REPLACED SAFETY VENT WHICH SECURED THE CAR.  J. MILLAZZO OF CHEMTREC AND SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE B. LUEBBERT WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

THE HOSE RUPTURED WHILE THE CARGO TANK WAS BEING UNLOADED.  EMPLOYEES APPROACHED THE VALVE FROM UPWIND TO CLOSE THE VALVE.  THE AMMONIA CLOUD DISPERSED IN THE AIR SO CLEANUP ACTIVITY WAS NOT NEEDED.  FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CONTACTED AND THREE PERSONS WERE SENT TO THE HOSPITAL FOR PRECAUTION AND WERE RELEASED 1 HOUR LATER.  THE HOSE ON THE CARGO TANK HAS BEEN REPLACED.  THE USE OF VEHICLE SAFETY CHECKLISTS IS BEING RE-EMPHASIZED.

ON 5/12/93 AT APPROXIMATELY 2:00 PM, OUR TRUCK, LOADED WITH (2) TEN CUBIN YARD CONT AINERS OF F006 ZINC/NICKEL FILTER CAKE, WAS IN TRANSIT TO INMETCO IN ELLWOOD CITY, PA.  WHEN THE LOAD ARRIVED IN ELLWOOD CITY, THE TRUCK MADE A SHARP TURN AT THE INTERSECTION OF RT 288 (ELLWOOD-WAMPUM ROAD) ONTO 5TH STREET.  AT THAT POINT, THE LOAD IN THE CONTAINER ON THE PUP TRAILER APPARENTLY SHIFTED AND A SMALL AMOUNT OF FILTER CAKE SLIPPED OUT FROM UNDER THE TARPED LUGGER BOX AND ONTO THE ROADWAY.  THE DRIVER STOPPED AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL MATERIAL.  OUR DRIVER ESTIMATED THE SPILL AT TWO TO THREE POUNDS PLUS ABOUT ONE-HALF GALLONS OF WATER.  HE SOAKED THIS WITH FLOOR DRY AND PLACED IT BACK INTO THE BOX.  APPARENTLY, THE ELLWOOD CITY POLICE HAD RECEIVED A COMPLAINT THAT SOMETHING HAD BEEN SPILLED AT THIS LOCATION AS THE DRIVER WAS SEEN CLEANING IT UP.  THE MATERIAL HAS A BRIGHT GREEN CHARACTERISTIC WHICH COULD HAVE BROUGHT ATTENTION TO WHOMEVER SAW HIM CLEANING IT UP.  LIEUTENANT WILLIAM R. BETTS, OF THE ELLWOOD CITY POLICE, NOT KNOWING WHAT THE MATERIAL WAS, CONTACTED THE LAWERENCE COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY.  THIS IN TURN ACTIVATED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE SYSTEM (THE RESPONSE TIME BY THE DER AND THE LCEMA WAS QUITE IMPRESSIVE).  FOLLOWING A DESCRIPTION OF THE TRUCK, LIEUTENANT BETTS LOCATED THE TRUCK AT THE MAIN GATE AT INMETCO. WITH LIEUTENANT BETTS HELP, THE DRIVER AND THE ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGER OF INMETCO, JOHN ONUSKA, WENT TO THE SPILL LOCATION.  THEY SWEPT THE AREA ONCE AGAIN TO ENSURE THERE WAS NO MORE RESIDUE AND DID FIND APPROXIMATELY A HANDFUL OF MATERIAL A SHORT DISTANCE AWAY, WHICH WAS COLLECTED AND THE AREA CLEANED UP.  THE REPORTABLE QUATITY OF THIS MATERIAL IS 10 POUNDS. THE TOTAL COLLECTION OF THIS MATERIAL WAS APPROXIMATELY  ONE COFFEE CAN FULL (2 TO 3 POUNDS). LIEUTENANT BETTS WITNESSED THE CLEAN-UP AND WAS SATISFIED.

column168: THE PACKAGE WAS TRAVELLING THROUGH OUR INDIANAPOLIS HUB SORT FACILITY WHEN IT APPARENTLY BROKE OPEN IN THE SECONDARY BOX SLIDE SORT AREA.  BEADS OF THE MERCURY WERE FOUND IN THE SORT SLIDE.  THE DG/SPILL SPECIALIST, JUDSON SEELYE IMMEDIATELY SUITED UP AND COMMENCED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL.  A MERCURY SPILL KIT WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE MERCURY AND SYRINGE - TYPE COLLECTOR BOTTLES WERE USED TO CONTAIN THE SUBSTANCE.  THE OUTER PACKAGE WAS FOUND ON THE OUTBOUND SLIDE AND THE PROCESS WAS REPEATED USING THE AFOREMENTIONED MATERIALS.  AFTER CONTAINMENT, THE SHIPPER USED A FEDERAL EXPRESS PACKAGING (OVERNIGHT TUBE).  THE SHIPMENT HAD NO MARKINGS, LABELLING OR SHIPING CERTIFICATION ON THE BOX.  AFTER THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED THE SPECIALIST THEN CALLED THE RECIEPENT, PRINCO INSTRUMENTS TO REQUEST A CURRENT MSDS ON THE ITEM AFTER LOOKING AT THE MSDS THE MATERIAL APPEARED TO BE AN UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  MR. SEELYE THEN CALLED OUR INTERNAL DANGEROUS GOODS ADMINISTRATION DEPARTMENT FOR FUTHER INSTRUCTIONS.  ONCE VERIFIED WE THEN CONTACTED DAVID KANE, SPECIAL AGENT, FAA AT 317-247-2567.  SPECIAL AGENT KANE SAID HE WOULD FOLLOW UP WITH MR. SEELYE FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION.

PACKAGE WAS REMOVED FROM AIRCRAFT FLIGHT 814 HOUSTON TO INDIANAPOLIS AFTER CREW NOTICED STRONG ODOR IN THE COCKPIT.  THE CREW WAS ON OXYGEN THE LAST 20 MINUTES OF THE FLIGHT BUT DID NOT DECLARE AN EMERGENCY.  THE STEEL DRUM WAS REMOVED AND INSPECTED FOR LEAKAGE.  THE DRUM WAS SLIGHTLY DENTED NEAR THE RING ON THE SIDE OF THE CAN.  THERE WAS VERY SLIGHT LEAKAGE FROM THE SIDE.  THE CAN WAS PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM AND HELD.  THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINSTRATION'S 24-HOUR DUTY OFFICER TIM CURTIS AT 312/247-2567.  THE PACKAGE WAS HELD AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION. TWO EMPLOYEES WENT TO A CLINIC FOR INHALATION OF THE FUMES.  THEY WERE TREATED AND RELEASED.
